    "title":  "Khúc Dạo Đầu Của Sương Trắng Và Sóng Đen",
    "content":  "{{Stub|Cần dịch phần trong cmt.\u003cbr\u003eCần up ảnh Thẻ Cốt Truyện Chương 4 Màn 1.}}\n{{Act Infobox\n|image          = Thẻ Cốt Truyện Chương 4 Màn 1.png\n|type           = Ma Thần\n|chapter        = Chương 4\n|actNum         = 1\n|prev           = Caribert\n|next           = Như Làn Mưa Nhẹ Không Rõ Nguyên Nhân\n|ARReq          = 40\n|rep            = Fontaine\n|repAmt         = 100\n}}\n\u0027\u0027\u0027Khúc Dạo Đầu Của Sương Trắng Và Sóng Đêm\u0027\u0027\u0027 là [[Màn 1]] thuộc [[Chương 4]] [[Nhiệm Vụ Ma Thần]].\n\n==Danh Sách Nhiệm Vụ==\n# [[Màn Dạo Đầu Của Kẻ Độc Diễn]]\n# [[Thành Phố Của Mưa Và Kỷ Niệm]]\n# [[Bóng Hình Lừa Dối Dưới Ánh Đèn]]\n\n==Tóm Tắt Trong Một Câu==\nNhà Lữ Hành và Paimon tạm biệt Dehya, sau đó quyết định đi đến Fontaine.\n\n==Tóm Lược==\n;Màn Dạo Đầu Của Kẻ Độc Diễn\n\nNhà Lữ Hành và Paimon đi đến [[Dịch Trạm Lữ Khách]]. Bỗng [[Paimon]] hồi tưởng lại lần đầu đến Sumeru, giúp [[Nahida]] ngăn chặn các hiền giả phản bội thần linh ở [[Giáo Viện Sumeru]]. Khi hai người chuẩn bị đến [[Fontaine]], [[Dehya]] đến Dịch Trạm Lữ Khách. Dehya mới làm xong ủy thác vận chuyển hàng hóa, đã đến chào Nhà Lữ Hành và Paimon. Cô hỏi về hành trình tiếp theo của hai người, Nhà Lữ Hành đáp sẽ đến Fontaine. Bất chợt một người Fontaine ném một ánh mắt ngờ vực lên đôi bạn đồng hành kia. Về phía Dehya, cô ngạc nhiên về quyết định đến Fontaine của Nhà Lữ Hành và Paimon, nhưng khi nhớ ra họ là nhà lữ hành nay đây mai đó, nên cô gợi ý Nhà Lữ Hành và Paimon đi theo những người lính đánh thuê giữa biên giới hai quốc gia dù biết hai người sẽ từ chối. Dehya thừa nhận, cô cảm thấy tiếc nuối khi người anh hùng của Sumeru rời đi như một cơn gió thoảng, nhưng cô vẫn chúc hai người thuận lợi trên chuyến hành trình tiếp theo. Sau khi hoàn thành công chuyện ở Sumeru, Nhà Lữ Hành và Paimon đến [[Cảng Romaritime]].\n\nLần đầu đến cảng, Paimon ấn tượng với công nghệ phát triển ở nơi đây. Hai người trò chuyện về những gì sẽ làm ở đất nước này, Nhà Lữ Hành nói nên gặp Thủy Thần ngay tức khắc, khiến Paimon tò mò về \"con người cá tính\" của Thủy Thần mà [[Nahida]] nhận xét. Paimon chỉ cho Nhà Lữ Hành hai người bản địa phía trước, nhờ hỏi họ để có thông tin về Thủy Thần. [[Rena]] và [[Etienne]] nói chuyện về phiên xét xử ở [[Tòa Án Fontaine]], so sánh giống như một buổi nhạc kịch. Paimon tiếp lời, bày tỏ sự lo lắng về độ nghiêm túc của phiên xét xử, và Rena tiếp lời rằng sẽ không có việc xét xử oan sai, bởi đã có Thẩm Phán Tối Cao [[Neuvillette]] cùng [[Cỗ Máy Chỉ Thị Phán Quyết]] được tạc đúc từ bàn tay của Thần. Paimon hỏi về cách gặp được thần, Etienne nói rằng Thủy Thần, Cô [[Furina]] sống ngay trong tòa án. Rena đoán trúng rằng hai người lữ khách này muốn nói chuyện với Thủy Thần nên nói rằng quy trình gặp được Thủy Thần Furina rất phức tạp, bởi Furina rất nổi tiếng trước công chúng nên phải đặt lịch trước. \n\nNhà Lữ Hành suy luận rằng tuy người dân Fontaine rất thích Thuỷ Thần, nhưng họ lại thiếu đôi chút sự kính nể dành cho cô ấy. Khi Paimon đưa ra đề nghị họ nên giành thời gian để khám phá thành phố thì Nhà Lữ Hành trông thấy một cô gái đang đứng ở rìa cảng và quyết định đi đến đó để kiểm tra xem cô ấy có ổn không. Cô gái nhắc về những kỉ niệm trong quá khứ nhưng hiện tại những kỉ niệm đó đã bị nhấn chìm dưới đáy biển, cô ấy nói một cách bí ẩn rằng rồi họ cũng sẽ bị nhấn chìm như vậy. Trước khi họ có thể tiếp tục trò chuyện, anh trai của cô ấy xuất hiện và cảm ơn họ vì đã chăm sóc [[Lynette]]. Thiếu niên hoạt bát kia liền giới thiệu tên của cậu ấy là [[Lyney]] và Paimon giải thích rằng Lynette đang trò chuyện với họ, điều đó đã làm Lyney ngạc nhiên vì Lynette rất hiếm khi trò chuyện với người lạ. Paimon hỏi về những gì mà Lynette đã nói, Lyney giải thích rằng đó là một \"lời tiên tri\" đã được lưu truyền khắp Fontaine . Sau đó Lyney đã chính thức chào hỏi cả hai. Biết được lý do mà họ ghé thăm Fontaine, Lyney đã đề nghị sẽ đưa họ đến Viện Ca Kịch.\n\u003c!--\nAs they make their way around, they are instead greeted by Furina and her entourage, surprising Paimon. Furina directly addresses the Traveler and Paimon, aware of their travels in the other nations but nonetheless welcomes them as the nation\u0027s Archon. She then asks them if they have the qualities to communicate with her as the person from before bows, having informed her of their arrival. The people believe that the Traveler had come to duel her, so the Traveler draws their sword out. [[Clorinde]] prepares to intercept, but Furina has her step down, commending their bravery to stand against a god. As a normal duel is too expected, Furina instead declares that they will have a duel in court, surprising the Traveler and Paimon as they had only just arrived in the nation. Furina then points out that they had just broken a law by releasing a flying object on the first three days of a month - referring to Paimon, thus giving legal grounds to arrest them. \n\nLyney objects to the order, believing Paimon to be something else, so Furina hears his claim. Lyney snaps his fingers, revealing a red cord tying the Traveler and Paimon, claiming that they had always arrived in the nation like this and thus the charges are no longer warranted. Furina is entertained and drops the charges. She then leaves, expecting a good performance from Lyney and Lynette later on. Paimon is left baffled by the encounter, while Lyney tells them that he had just remembered such a law and made preparations just incase. He then reveals that he and his sister are having their first performance in the court, which serves as an opera house when a trial is not in session. \n\nLyney gives them a Magic Pocket and tells them more about the prophecy; everyone is born with sin, and not even the Hydro Archon could absolve them of it. One day, the water levels would rise in Fontaine, drowning the people and leaving the Hydro Archon alone and weeping on her throne, of which the sins of the nation could be washed away. Paimon asks to why people had sin in them, but Lyney is not able to give a clear answer on it as it is only based on rumors. Regardless, with further study, the people believed the claims to be baseless until recently when the nation\u0027s water levels began to rise, thus the Magic Pockets were to allow people in the waterside to store their belongings in them as they left.\n\nAfter giving the Magic Pockets to nearby people, the two return to Lyney, who wanted to have the people prepared in the worst case scenario. Before they could leave, he asks them to help gather some [[Romaritime Flower]]s. Once they do so, they spot a girl pickpocketing the people and they concoct a plan to catch her incase she tried to flee. With some time passed, they decide to check on Lyney, who had returned the stolen items; the thief had fled, but Lyney had hurt himself and they aborted the pursuit. With everything finally resolved, they take the aquabus, just as a familiar person manages to get on in time, who they recognize as [[Charlotte]].\n\nCharlotte is surprised to see the Traveler and Paimon, not having heard anything about their visit to the nation. She introduces herself to Lyney and Lynette before they talk about the talk of the nation, mostly a case with young women disappearing over a 20-year spree with no resolution in sight. Once they arrive, Charlotte leaves for an interview, so Lyney asks the Traveler and Paimon to follow him to their home.\n\n;Thành Phố Của Mưa Và Kỷ Niệm\nArriving at Lyney and Lynette\u0027s home, they run into [[Freminet]], asking him where everyone else went. Freminet tells them that they all went out, prompting Lyney to state that \"[[Arlecchino|Father]]\" was returning soon and introduces the Traveler and Paimon to him. Freminet then asks Lyney about something in private, after which he collects the materials for the Magic Pockets. Suddenly, the sky begins to darken as it rains, surprising Paimon. Lyney tells them that the change in weather is usually when trials were taking place in the opera house while Freminet looks at the sky. He tells Paimon that he heard about a rumor that the Dragon of Water used to live in Fontaine and while no one knew where it went, people believed that when it wept, the skies would cloud out and rain.\n\nThe rain lasts longer than usual, so Lyney decides to finish some business and asks Freminet to take the supplies to the workshop. Freminet is too scared to go however, being an introvert, so the Traveler offers to do so in his stead. Arriving at Beaumont Workshop, they hand the items to Estelle, who tells them they don\u0027t have to pay, as Lyney had done so in advance. Paimon is impressed by the machine that she\u0027s using. Estelle tells her that the machine runs on Indemnitium, a source of power made from the trials at the court. She then talks about another source of energy before being rudely interrupted by [[Traund]] and his lackeys, associates the [[Confrerie of Cabriere]]. As the Traveler tries try to leave, [[Tartaglia|Childe]] unexpectedly appears and warns the group of their own debt to [[Northland Bank]]. Paimon waves at Childe, surprising him as he did not expect to see them in the nation, as he was starting to get bored and their arrival meant that things would get interesting.\n\nChilde continues his talk with the Traveler and Paimon, angering Traund to the point that he and his lackeys attack. Childe easily overwhelms them, with the Traveler and Paimon serving as witnesses. Traund then realizes that Childe is actually one of the [[Eleven Fatui Harbingers]], but Childe suddenly loses control of his Hydro weapons, which Traund takes the opportunity to attack, only to be knocked out by a single punch. The Traveler, Paimon and Childe wonder what happened, though Childe still has his [[Delusion]] as a backup. Paimon asks what he\u0027s doing in Fontaine; Childe tells them that he has been in a bad mood recently and began to feel something stirring inside him, which Paimon surmises might be tied to his Hydro Vision weakening. Childe then tells them about his time in the [[Abyss]], including his meeting with [[Skirk]], who took him as an apprentice because he had \"it\" on him and her lessons would help in the future. \n\nChilde then realizes a sufficient amount of time passed and reveals that while he\u0027s been idling around in Fontaine, he\u0027s been sparring with their official Champion Duelists. Childe explains that before going to court, the accused are given one chance to redeem their honor against a Champion Duelist, who are some of the nation\u0027s strongest fighters. If they win, the charges would be dropped, but if they lost, they would have to go to trial, though most simply die and rarely anyone was freed in such a manner. Childe states that he was about to spar with Clorinde and gives the Traveler his Vision, as he did not want it to get in the way of his duel with her with recent events before leaving.\n\nHeading to the [[Fountain of Lucine]], the Traveler hears a mysterious voice as Lynette appears to greet them. They ask her about the voice, so she gives them a theory about tears being intense emotions. She then takes them inside the opera house to catch up with Lyney, believing a talk with him would allow him to cool his nerves before the big show. Inside, Lyney gives them tickets to the best seats before being called by [[Cowell]] to handle the props. As they go inside to their seats, they find a man next to them, resulting in an awkward moment. The man then apologizes, with Paimon introducing herself and the Traveler. The man had heard about their travels across Teyvat and attempts to introduce himself, only for Lyney to come in and call him by his name, Neuvillette, being pleased to see he was going to watch his show. Lyney properly introduces Neuvillette to the two, even showing the seat at the top of the court which he uses. Neuvillette then tells the Traveler that Furina was trying to get their attention, so they look at her briefly, which he deems enough to satisfy her.\n\nAs the audience trickles into the opera, Lyney and Lynette begin the show. Lyney brings in a water tank and performs a trick to make Lynette disappear before she reappears, which entertains Furina and the guests. Paimon is left shocked at how he was able to pull it off, while Neuvillette tells her that she should be focusing on the show and not the hidden tricks. He then pulls out another magic box and pulls two audience members. In the process Lyney has some difficulty in finishing the trick. While he successfully gets out of his own box, the other one fails to do so, instead resulting in the water tank from earlier breaking, leaving Lyney shocked. Neuvillette then orders the entire opera into lockdown. After a quick investigation, Neuvillette reveals that Cowell was found dead in the box and the girl had gone missing in a manner similar to the disappearance case. Furina then declares Lyney a suspect due to the circumstances involved. Neuvillette then asks Furina if she was going to press charges on Lyney, which surprises her, but with the audience believing otherwise, ends up declaring a duel between her and the Traveler.\n\nNeuvillette then declares a trial the following day, assigning the Traveler as Lyney\u0027s attorney, while Furina wonders what the Traveler would do in the trial. As everyone leaves, the Traveler and Paimon talk with Lyney and Lynette, who are relieved that they have their support for the upcoming trial.\n\n;Bóng Hình Lừa Dối Dưới Ánh Đèn\nAs they go to collect evidence, the Traveler and Paimon speak to [[Esmond]], who believes that Lyney is truly the suspect. Searching around, they begin to build up a case to defend Lyney. During the process, they run into a mysterious woman and men in black suits, who introduce themselves as [[Navia]], [[Silver]] and [[Melus]] of the [[Spina di Rosula]], an investigation organization. Navia agrees to help, as she sees the trials as something more serious and her group is also after the truth behind the disappearances. After showing how they performed the magic box trick, Lyney and Lynette are escorted out, leaving the Traveler, Paimon, Navia and her associates to investigate. During the investigation, the group discovers many irregularities and jot it down on paper. Navia suggests going out to collect their thoughts, but Melus tells them that as they are now associated with the twins, they cannot leave until the trial concludes. As they need some tea and snacks, Melus reveals a baking stove and Silver ingredients, which Navia uses to make macarons. The trio then leave to collect more information, so the Traveler waits the following day for the trial to start.\n\nThe next day, Neuvillette declares the trial to start while both parties give their statements. When Lyney maintains his innocence, Furina points out that around the half-way mark, there was a loud thud and expresses doubt that he could not have heard it, surprising him, while the scales tilt in her favor. She then exposes them as members of from the [[House of the Hearth]], surprising the Traveler and Paimon as this meant that they were [[Fatui]] agents. This results in the audience supporting Furina\u0027s claims while she notices the Traveler is speechless, believing herself to have won. Neuvillette asks Lyney if what Furina said was true, which he confirms, resulting in the scale dropping even further towards her favor. The Traveler then requests for the court to be adjourned, which Neuvillette grants for an hour.\n\nAt the opera\u0027s backstage, Lyney expresses surprise that Furina would have dug deep into their past, while the Traveler and Paimon are upset by the deception. The twins apologize for deceiving them, knowing of their records with the Fatui, but Lyney insists that he is innocent in this case. The Traveler agrees to help to see justice served correctly, so Lyney begins telling them his recollection of the events - he wanted to investigate the Oratrice\u0027s core, but ended up retreating when a voice called out to him. When he got back into the tunnel, he saw the smashed vase and scattered clothes, but did not think much about it as the countdown was about to finish. They then return to court, having had what they needed to refute Furina\u0027s accusations and expose a flaw in her reasoning, gaining some of the audience\u0027s support.  \n\nFurina manages to regain some of the audience\u0027s sway after the Traveler is unable to deduce some of the truth, but the Traveler then realizes that they need to go from another angle and request to inspect Cowell\u0027s belongings, believing he may have used the water from the tank to take another form. Furina finds this absurd, as it\u0027s only a magic trick, but as the trial can\u0027t continue further, Neuvillette agrees to the request. Esmond then comes in and reveals that Cowell\u0027s bag had labeled tubes of water from the Primordial Sea and that he belonged to an organization selling illegal drugs. Navia then realizes that something is wrong and leaves with her associates.\n\nWith the new evidence supporting Lyney\u0027s innocence, Neuvillette allows the Traveler to continue with their hypothesis, which tilts the scales towards Lyney\u0027s favor. Furina on the other hand becomes worried about having wrongly accused someone, even thinking that their reasoning is correct. Neuvillette then brings in Vaughn, having been informed of new evidence found; the same water was found in Lyney\u0027s belongings. Furina uses the opportunity to cement her claim, knowing that the Traveler has nothing to defend against it. Before the sentencing could start, Navia then bursts in with new evidence, revealing the box from before and asks Lyney to repeat the trick. Lyney snaps his fingers and the missing woman comes out, confessing to the entire crime and that she was actually [[Liliane]], not Halsey. She was the thief that the Traveler and Lyney were chasing at the harbor and when she came to the show to relax, she became terrified when he mentioned the [[Fortress of Meropide]], believing he was onto her.\n\nNow relating the story in Liliane\u0027s perspective, the scales tip towards Lyney\u0027s favor, leaving Furina shocked and unable to muster any words. She admits defeat and Neuvillette puts the information into the Oratice, which hands out a \"Not Guilty\" verdict to Lyney and Lynette, though Neuvillette does remark that both Lyney and Liliane\u0027s conduct should warrant additional investigation. Neuvillette then realizes that Vaughn was Cowell\u0027s accomplice, which results in Furina yelling at him for deceiving her judgement. Neuvillette suggests he confess to everything and seek the protection of the Gardes. Vaughn begins to confess to the entire plot, but before he could reveal the identity of the \"Boss\", he dissolves into water, forcing Neuvillette to order another inspection, though no evidence is yielded.\n\nWith the case over, Lyney and Lynette talk to the Traveler again, thanking them for their help and apologizing for deceiving them; as orphans, their goals aligned with the House of the Hearth and the Knave. After their parents died, he and Lynette were able to survive after watching a street performer\u0027s show. After being adopted by a noble, Lyney became horrified when he learned that he had trafficked her to another person. He went to rescue her, but when he arrived, the Knave had already rescued her and several others before offering them a spot in the House of the Hearth. Lyney reveals that the Knave (also known as Arlecchino) believed in the prophecy thus apart from trying to take the Hydro Gnosis, would try to use it first to protect their home. Lyney apologizes again for the deception but promises to help just as himself should they need it.\n\nAs they prepare to leave the opera, Navia and her associates manage to catch up to them, believing that the case is not solved yet. However, she learns from them that they were only there to defend Lyney and not the disappearing case. Despite this, she decides to have a farewell meal at [[Hotel Debord]], which the Traveler and Paimon agree to.\n--\u003e\n\u003c!--\n==Achievements==\n{{Achievement Topic Table|quest=Prelude of Blancheur and Noirceur}}\n--\u003e\n\n==Thư Viện==\n\u003cgallery\u003e\nChapter IV Act I and II.png|Thông Báo Trong Chương Trình Đặc Biệt\nThông Báo Chương 4 Màn 1 Và Màn 2.png|Thông Báo Nhiệm Vụ Ma Thần\n\u003c/gallery\u003e\n\n==Ngôn Ngữ Khác==\n{{Other Languages\n|en        = Prelude of Blancheur and Noirceur\n|zhs       = 白露与黑潮的序诗\n|zhs_rm    = Báilù yǔ Hēicháo de Xùshī\n|zht       = 白露與黑潮的序詩\n|zht_rm    = Báilù yǔ Hēicháo de Xùshī\n|zh_tl     = Prelude of White Dew and Black Tides\n|ja        = 白露と黒潮の序詩\n|ja_rm     = Hakuro to Kokuchou no Joshi{{Assumed}}\n|ja_tl     = \n|ko        = 흰 이슬과 검은 물결\u003c-\u003e의 서시\n|ko_rm     = Huin Iseulgwa Geomeun Mulgyeol-ui Seosi\n|ko_tl     = Prelude of White Dew and Black Waves\n|es        = Preludio de la claridad y la oscuridad\n|es_tl     = Prelude of Light and Darkness\n|fr        = Prélude de blancheur et de noirceur\n|fr_tl     = Prelude of Whiteness and Blackness\n|ru        = Прелюдия белых рос и чёрных волн\n|ru_tl     = Prelude of White Dew and Black Waves\n|th        = บทนำแห่งน้ำค้างขาวและคลื่นดำ\n|th_rm     = \n|th_tl     = \n|vi        = Khúc Dạo Đầu Của Sương Trắng Và Sóng Đen\n|vi_tl     = \n|de        = Präludium von Blancheur und Noirceur\n|de_tl     = \n|id        = Pendahuluan Kabut Putih dan Ombak Hitam\n|id_tl     = Prelude of White Mist and Black Waves\n|pt        = Prelúdio do Orvalho Branco e da Maré Escura\n|pt_tl     = \n|tr        = Siyah ve Beyazın Başlangıcı\n|tr_tl     = Prelude of Black and White\n|it        = Preludio di Blancheur e Noirceur\n|it_tl     = Prelude of Blancheur and Noirceur\n}}\n\n==Lịch Sử Cập Nhật==\n{{Change History|4.0}}\n\n==Điều Hướng==\n{{Archon Quest Navbox|Chương 4}}\n\n[[en:Prelude of Blancheur and Noirceur]]\n[[es:Preludio de la claridad y la oscuridad]]\n[[ja:白露と黒潮の序詩]]\n[[pl:Preludium blancheur i noirceur]]\n[[pt-br:Prelúdio do Orvalho Branco e da Maré Escura]]\n[[ru:Прелюдия белых рос и чёрных волн]]"
